1️⃣ Launching an AWS EC2 Instance (Complete Flow)
✅ Step A — Launch EC2 (Console Steps)

Go to AWS Console → EC2 → Launch Instance

Choose AMI (Amazon Linux / Ubuntu / Windows)

Choose Instance Type (t3.micro, m5.large, etc.)

Configure:

VPC

Subnet (Public / Private)

Auto-assign Public IP (if needed)

Configure Storage:

Root Volume (EBS)

Optional additional EBS volumes

Configure Security:

Security Group (Inbound rules)

SSH (22)

RDP (3389)

HTTP (80)

HTTPS (443)

Configure Advanced Settings:

Attach IAM Role (recommended)

Launch with Key Pair

🔎 What Happens Behind the Scenes

When you click Launch, AWS:

Allocates compute capacity in an Availability Zone

Creates Elastic Network Interface (ENI)

Assigns private IP from subnet CIDR

Assigns public IP (if enabled)

Applies Security Group rules

Attaches root EBS volume

Attaches additional EBS volumes (if configured)

Binds IAM Role to instance

Starts hypervisor VM

EC2 runs on AWS Nitro Hypervisor architecture.

🔐 SSH / RDP Access

Linux:

ssh -i mykey.pem ec2-user@<public-ip>

Windows:

Download RDP file

Decrypt password using private key

Security Group must allow inbound port.

🌐 Networking Details
Public Subnet

Route table contains:

0.0.0.0/0 → Internet Gateway (IGW)

Instance has Public IP

Direct internet access allowed

Private Subnet

No direct Internet Gateway route

Uses:

NAT Gateway (for outbound internet)

VPC Endpoint (for AWS services)

Used for backend services

🧱 2️⃣ EC2 + EBS (Block Storage)

Equivalent to Azure Managed Disk.

🔹 Scenario

Attach an extra EBS volume to EC2 as /data.

✅ Step A — Create EBS Volume

Go to EC2 → Volumes → Create Volume

Choose:

Availability Zone (same as EC2)

Type:

gp3 (General SSD)

io2 (Provisioned IOPS)

st1 (HDD)

Size

Create

✅ Step B — Attach Volume

Select volume → Attach Volume

Choose EC2 instance

Device name (e.g., /dev/xvdf)

✅ Step C — Mount in Linux
lsblk
sudo mkfs -t ext4 /dev/xvdf
sudo mkdir /data
sudo mount /dev/xvdf /data

Persist after reboot:

echo "/dev/xvdf /data ext4 defaults,nofail 0 2" | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
📂 3️⃣ EFS (Shared File Storage)

Equivalent to Azure Files.

🔹 Scenario

Multiple EC2 instances need shared access.

✅ Step A — Create EFS

Go to EFS → Create File System

Choose:

VPC

Subnets (creates Mount Targets in each AZ)

Configure:

Performance Mode (General Purpose / Max IO)

Throughput Mode (Bursting / Provisioned)

✅ Step B — Configure Security

EFS uses NFS (port 2049)

Security Group must allow:

Inbound 2049 from EC2 security group

✅ Step C — Mount EFS

Install NFS utils:

sudo yum install -y nfs-utils

Mount:

sudo mkdir /shared
sudo mount -t nfs4 <efs-dns-name>:/ /shared

All EC2 instances now share the same file system.

🗂 4️⃣ S3 Usage from EC2

Equivalent to Azure Blob Storage.

S3 is object storage.

✅ Step A — Create S3 Bucket

Go to S3 → Create Bucket

Choose:

Unique bucket name

Region

Keep private (recommended)

✅ Step B — Attach IAM Role to EC2

Go to IAM → Roles → Create Role

Trusted entity → EC2

Attach policy:

AmazonS3FullAccess

Or custom least-privilege policy

Attach role to EC2

✅ Step C — Access S3 from EC2

Install AWS CLI:

sudo yum install awscli -y

Upload:

aws s3 cp file.txt s3://mybucket/

Download:

aws s3 cp s3://mybucket/file.txt .

No keys required — IAM Role provides temporary credentials.

🔐 IAM Role Flow (Equivalent to Managed Identity)

EC2 calls Instance Metadata Service (IMDS):

http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/

AWS STS provides temporary credentials

AWS CLI / SDK uses credentials automatically

Credentials rotate automatically

No hardcoded access keys required.

🔎 Internal Differences Summary
Feature	EBS	EFS	S3
Type	Block	File (NFS)	Object
Scope	Single AZ	Multi-AZ	Regional
Shared across instances	❌	✅	Via API
Mounted like disk	✅	✅	❌
Best for	OS / DB	Shared apps	Backup / static / data lake
🧠 Production Example Architecture

Frontend EC2 root disk → EBS (gp3)

Database EC2 → Provisioned IOPS EBS

Shared uploads → EFS

Backups → S3

Logs → S3

Private backend → Private Subnet + NAT

Public frontend → Public Subnet + ALB

🚨 Common Mistakes

❌ EBS volume in different Availability Zone
❌ Not opening NFS port 2049 for EFS
❌ Wide-open Security Group (0.0.0.0/0 for all ports)
❌ Hardcoding AWS access keys instead of IAM Role
❌ Making S3 bucket public accidentally

